SIMPLE: milliner
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Milliner
<hw>Mil"li*ner</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[From
<ets>Milaner</ets> an inhabitant of <ets>Milan</ets>, in Italy; hence, a
man from <ets>Milan</ets> who imported women's finery.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Formerly, a man who imported and dealt in small
articles of a miscellaneous kind, especially such as please the fancy of
women.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>No <qex>milliner</qex> can so fit his customers with gloves.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A person who designs, makes, trims, or deals in
hats, bonnets, headdresses, etc., for women.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Man milliner</b></col>, <cd>a man who makes or deals in
millinery, that occupation having been at one time predominantly
performed by women; hence, contemptuously, a man who is busied with
trifling occupations or embellishments.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Millinery</ent>⟦br⟧
